2. Root Cause
All three symptoms share a single root cause: the system makes attach-or-leak decisions by comparing a bi-encoder cosine score to a fixed global threshold. A bi-encoder (e5-large) encodes each text independently into a vector, so two cases describing the same outage in different words can land at only 0.82–0.88 cosine — below the bar — and leak.
There is no single threshold that works for every topic. Tight topics (a specific error code) have members at 0.93+, while loose topics (“login is slow”) sit near 0.80. Set the bar high and loose topics leak; set it low and unrelated cases merge. Because every leaked fragment can independently grow into its own alert, the same topic spawns several alerts, and near-miss cases are stranded as singletons.
The fix is not a better threshold. It is a better judge of “same issue or not,” applied through a RAG retrieve-and-rerank pipeline against two indexes.
3. Proposed Design: Two-Index RAG
Core idea in one sentence: retrieve candidates cheaply with the fast bi-encoder, then decide accurately with a cross-encoder reranker — against two indexes: a frozen one of known topics (Pass 1) and a self-growing one built from the leaked cases themselves (Pass 2).
3.1 Two indexes
• Index A — Known red topics. Frozen, built once from the labelled topics. One representative vector per topic. Pass 1 reads from it.
• Index B — Emergent clusters. Starts empty and grows from the stream. Each leaked case joins a cluster here or plants a new one. Pass 2 reads and writes this index. This write-back is what groups previously unseen families of cases — the piece the current system lacks.
3.2 Two scoring stages
• Bi-encoder ANN (fast, blunt). The existing e5-large embedding plus Approximate Nearest Neighbor search narrows thousands of candidates to the top ~10. It only needs to avoid missing the right candidate, not make the final call.
• Cross-encoder reranker (slow, sharp). Takes the case and a candidate together as one input and scores how truly same-issue they are. It reads both texts jointly, so it catches paraphrases the cosine score misses.
3.3 Two operating points
The same reranker is used with two different bars, because Pass 1 and Pass 2 have different risk profiles:
• Pass 1 — strict bar (high precision). Only attach to a known topic when confident; a false attach to a known topic is costly.
• Pass 2 — generous bar (high recall). Group leaked cases aggressively; a wrong merge is later corrected by the async merge sweep.
Using one threshold for both decisions is why the current system cannot win precision and recall at the same time.
3.4 Async reconciliation (off the hot path)
RAG retrieves one case at a time and has no notion that two clusters are the same family. Three background jobs, all running off the latency path, close that gap:
• Centroid / exemplar refresh. When a cluster grows, recompute its representative vector and upsert it so retrieval stays accurate.
• Merge sweep. Periodically compare active cluster exemplars; if two are close enough and share high-signal tokens (error codes, endpoints), merge them. This removes duplicate alerts.
• Expiry with resurrection. Move expired clusters to a cold pool instead of deleting them. A recurrence retrieves the cold exemplar and resurrects the cluster rather than spawning a new alert.
3.5 The hot path, end to end
1. Embed case (e5-large)                         ~30 ms
2. Pass 1: ANN over Index A  -> top ~10           ~10 ms
3. Cross-encoder rerank (strict bar)              ~80 ms
    match  -> attach to known topic (done)
    no match -> leaks to Pass 2

4. Pass 2: ANN over Index B  -> top ~10           ~10 ms
5. Cross-encoder rerank (generous bar)            ~80 ms
    match existing cluster -> attach + write back
    match singleton        -> form watchlist (2)
    match nothing          -> plant new singleton
6. Promote watchlist -> alert at size >= 3
  Async (off path): refresh, merge sweep, expiry/resurrect
